{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S4 — RFC 7662 token-introspection verifier\n\n## Why\nIntrospection completes the \"validate against an external Authorization Server\" story for providers\nthat issue **opaque** access tokens (or where instant revocation matters) — Keycloak, Okta, Auth0,\nWorkOS all expose a standard `/introspect` endpoint. It is the pattern the SDK's own `simple-auth`\nexample demonstrates.\n\n## What\nAdd an **`IntrospectionTokenVerifier`** to `src/rebar/_mcp_auth.py`, activated by including\n`introspection` in the `mcp.auth_strategies` list (the strategy-selection config key **introduced by\nS2**, this story's dependency — not a pre-existing seam), with flat config keys THIS story registers: `auth_introspection_endpoint`,\n`auth_introspection_client_id`, `auth_introspection_client_secret_env` (NAME of an env var holding\nthe client secret — no plaintext secret in config), `auth_introspection_cache_ttl` (seconds, default\n0 = no caching), `auth_introspection_allow_private_host` (bool, default `false`), and\n`auth_introspection_allow_missing_aud` (bool, default `false`). It does not take a per-verifier\naudience — it validates against the single `auth_resource_server_url` (S2). It POSTs the token\n(RFC 7662) with client authentication, accepts only `active: true`, and maps the response into an\n`AccessToken` (all RFC 7662 response fields are OPTIONAL, so each has a defined fallback): `scope`\n(a space-delimited string per §2.2) is split into the scopes list (absent → empty list),\n`exp`→`expires_at` (absent → `None`, per Expiry below), `sub`→`subject` (absent → `None`), and\n`client_id`→`client_id` (absent → falls back to `sub`, else `\"unknown\"`); and stamps `resource=auth_resource_server_url` so the composite\ncheck passes. NOTE: the SDK's `IntrospectionTokenVerifier` is an **example, not an exported/hardened\nclass** — this story WRITES its own (adapting the example), it does not import it. Registers its keys\nin `MCP_ENV_VARS`/`server.json`; the regenerated `mcp-reference.md`/`env-vars.md` pick these up via\nS1's fixes making `gen_mcp_reference.py`/`gen_env_registry.py` iterate `MCP_ENV_VARS`.\n\n## Approach & rationale\nAdapt the SDK `simple-auth` example (the blessed reference) and add the production hardening its\ndocstring says it lacks: client authentication on the introspection call, a short/off-by-default\ncache keyed on a token hash, strict audience handling, and fail-closed transport errors. Reuse the\nalready-present `httpx`.\n\n## Scope\nThe introspection verifier only, on the S2 seam. Subset of the epic. Depends on S2. Independent of\nS3/S5/S6.\n\n## Security\nBoundary-crossing. Requirements:\n- Call the introspection endpoint over authenticated TLS (`client_secret_basic`, secret from\n  `auth_introspection_client_secret_env`), **HTTPS-only** (an `http://` endpoint is rejected at\n  construction), bounded timeout. Private/link-local endpoint hosts (RFC 1918, loopback,\n  `169.254.0.0/16`) are **rejected by default**; an operator with a legitimate internal AS sets\n  `auth_introspection_allow_private_host=true` to opt out.\n- Accept only `active:true`. **Audience:** RFC 7662 §2.2 permits `aud` to be a JSON string OR an\n  array of strings — the check passes if `auth_resource_server_url` equals the string form or is a\n  member of the array form. If the AS omits `aud` (many do), the default is to **reject**\n  (fail-closed); an operator whose AS scopes tokens to this resource by other means sets\n  `auth_introspection_allow_missing_aud=true` to accept aud-absent tokens (documented risk in S7).\n- **Fail-closed transport:** a non-200, timeout, or malformed response **raises** (composite treats\n  as non-acceptance → deny); it is never cached. Only `active:true` positives are cached.\n- **Cache:** keyed on a **hash** of the token (never the plaintext). A positive is cached until\n  `min(now + auth_introspection_cache_ttl, token_exp)` — the earlier of (now + the configured\n  duration) and the token's own absolute expiry (both absolute epoch times; `cache_ttl` is a\n  duration in seconds, `token_exp` is epoch seconds, so they are combined via `now + cache_ttl`, not\n  compared directly). `auth_introspection_cache_ttl` **defaults to 0** (no caching) — documented\n  tradeoff: caching positives delays the effect of revocation up to the TTL, undercutting the\n  \"instant revocation\" rationale, so caching is opt-in.\n- **Expiry:** when the response includes `exp`, set `AccessToken.expires_at` from it (a real\n  positive value). When `active:true` but `exp` is absent (RFC 7662 permits it), set\n  `expires_at=None` — validity is then bounded by re-introspection (cache default 0 → every request\n  re-checks the AS) and, when caching is enabled, by the `now + cache_ttl` cache bound. Never emit\n  `expires_at=0` (the SDK reads a falsy value as no-expiry while looking like a set value).\n- Tokens/secrets never logged.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The `auth_introspection_*` flat keys are registered in `MCP_ENV_VARS`/`server.json` and appear\n      in the regenerated `docs/mcp-reference.md`/`docs/env-vars.md` (via S1's generator fixes that make\n      them iterate `MCP_ENV_VARS`), and `scripts/check_server_manifest.py` passes.\n- [ ] Unit test (tier: unit against the real verifier; the irreducible boundary — the introspection\n      HTTP call — is a stateful fake fed production-shaped RFC 7662 responses) asserts an `active:true`\n      response with a matching `aud` and an `exp` → an `AccessToken` with expected scopes,\n      `resource==auth_resource_server_url`, and a positive `expires_at`; and that an `active:true`\n      response OMITTING `exp` yields `expires_at=None` (never 0), with validity bounded by\n      re-introspection/cache (observable oracle: `expires_at is None`).\n- [ ] Unit tests assert rejection for: `active:false` (returns None); a response OMITTING `aud` when\n      `auth_introspection_allow_missing_aud=false` (fail-closed reject) — and acceptance of the same\n      response when the key is `true`; a mismatched `aud`; and an `aud` supplied as an ARRAY that\n      does/does not contain `auth_resource_server_url` (accept/reject respectively) — each a distinct\n      negative control. Also assert `scope` given as a space-delimited string is split into the\n      expected scopes list.\n- [ ] Unit test asserts a non-200 / timeout / malformed response **raises** (→ composite\n      non-acceptance/deny) and is **not** cached (observable oracle: a subsequent call re-hits the\n      fake), while an `active:true` positive is cached until `min(now + cache_ttl, token_exp)` and\n      the cache is keyed on the SHA-256 hex digest of the token (observable oracle: every cache key\n      is a 64-char hex string and no cache key contains the raw token substring).\n- [ ] Unit test asserts construction-time guards: the introspection request carries\n      `client_secret_basic` (secret sourced from `auth_introspection_client_secret_env`); an `http://`\n      endpoint is rejected; and a private/link-local host is rejected by default and accepted only\n      with `auth_introspection_allow_private_host=true` (observable oracle: the fake receives Basic\n      auth; rejection at construction for the http/private cases).\n- [ ] Integration test (tier: integration — httpx `ASGITransport` wrapping the MCP server; the\n      external RFC 7662 `/introspect` endpoint is the SAME stateful fake used in the unit tests,\n      injected via the verifier's httpx client so NO real network call is made) asserts an\n      introspection-validated token → 200 end-to-end, and an `active:false`/absent token → 401.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass.\n\n## Compatibility\nAdditive verifier, opt-in via the `introspection` strategy. No change to other verifiers or stdio."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784080616998354001,"uuid":"d7f1581b-5c76-4233-8b55-25aba2d27fb5"}